terior leads"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ECG findings described in the stem are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Eatrial flutter\u003C/strong\u003E, which is identified by a \u0027sawtooth\u0027 pattern, particularly visible in the inferior leads (II, III, and aVF). This pattern is due to the rapid atrial rate, typically around 300 beats per minute, with a variable ventricular response depending on the degree of atrioventricular block.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eirregularly irregular rhythm with no distinct P waves\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of atrial fibrillation, not atrial flutter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EST segment elevation in the anterior leads\u003C/strong\u003E is indicative of an anterior myocardial infarction, not atrial flutter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Edelta wave with a short PR interval\u003C/strong\u003E is seen in Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome, not atrial flutter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eprolonged QT interval\u003C/strong\u003E can be associated with various conditions, including electrolyte imbalances and certain medications, but it is not a feature of atrial flutter.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Atrial flutter is characterised by a \u0027sawtooth\u0027 pattern on an ECG, particularly visible in the inferior leads.","The atrial rate in atrial flutter is typically around 300 beats per minute, with a variable ventricular response depending on conduction."],"references":["Foy S, Levis JT. ECG diagnosis: Type I atrial flutter. Perm J. 2014 Spring;18(2):e128. doi: 10.7812/TPP/13-132. PMID: 24867555; PMCID: PMC4022567.","Rodriguez Ziccardi M, Goyal A, Maani CV. Atrial Flutter. [Updated 2022 Dec 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK540985/","Bagliani G, Leonelli FM, De